				"string" : "## Named Principles\n\nIngalls explicitly formulates a set of general design principles, including:\n\n* **Personal Mastery** — a system must be comprehensible to a single individual.\n* **Good Design** — minimal unchangeable parts; maximal generality; uniform framework.\n* **Objects** — the universe of computation consists of objects distinguished and referenced uniformly.\n* **Automatic Storage Management** — essential for a true object metaphor.\n* **Messages** — computation occurs by sending messages to objects.\n* **Uniform Metaphor** — one metaphor applied consistently at all levels.\n* **Modularity** — components must not depend on internal details of others.\n* **Classification** — new classes must stand on equal footing with system classes.\n* **Polymorphism** — programs specify behavior, not representation.\n* **Factoring and Leverage** — structure enables system-wide amplification of small changes.\n* **Reactive User Interface** — every user-accessible component can present itself for inspection and manipulation.\n* **No Separate Operating System** — system services are integrated into the language itself.\n* **Natural Selection** — well-designed languages persist until supplanted by better ones.\n\nThese principles are presented as general criteria for evaluating and designing computing systems, not merely as Smalltalk-specific doctrine.\n"
